<ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Yugoslavia</ENAMEX> is a step closer to ending its <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">years</ENAMEX> of isolation and socialist power .
<ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Yugoslavia</ENAMEX> 's parliament <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">today</ENAMEX> appointed a new government backing reformist President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Vojislav Kostunica</ENAMEX> .
It 's the country 's <ENAMEX TYPE="ORDINAL">first</ENAMEX> communist - free government in <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">more than half a century</ENAMEX> .
The new cabinet won approval in both chambers of parliament and from deputies of <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Yugoslavia</ENAMEX> 's <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">two</ENAMEX> republics -- <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Serbia</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Montenegro</ENAMEX> .
The new government is key for reformists to cement their position in power .
<ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">Last month 's</ENAMEX> mass uprising forced former President <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Slobodan Milosevic</ENAMEX> to admit defeat in presidential elections .
